# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bird-s-milk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Wedel is one of the most recognized chocolate confectioneries in Poland, having exclusive rights for the name *Ptasie mleczko*.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Its owner created the original "bird's milk" in 1936.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Other confectionery producers also make similar candies named differently (e.g., *Alpejskie mleczko*, "Alpine milk").
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Nonetheless, *Ptasie mleczko* is often used to refer to similar candies with vanilla, cream, lemon or chocolate flavour.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In Russia, *ptichye moloko* (птичье молоко) is both a popular candy and a famous soufflé cake derived from the Polish candy.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] The brand was introduced in the 1960s during the Soviet era, and continues to be used by companies operating the factories which produced these candies and cakes since that time.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] The confectionery is also produced in other post-Soviet states, such as Ukraine.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] The concept of avian milk (Ancient Greek: ὀρνίθων γάλα, *ornithon gala*) stretches back to ancient Greece.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Aristophanes uses "the milk of the birds" in the plays *The Birds* and *The Wasps* as a proverbial rarity.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] The expression is also found in Strabo's *Geographica* where the island of Samos is described as a *blest country,* to which *those who praise it do not hesitate to apply the proverb that "it produces even bird's milk" (φέρει καί ὀρνίθων γάλα)*.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] A similar expression *lac gallinaceum* (Latin for chicken's milk) was also later used by Petronius (38.1) and Pliny the Elder (Plin.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] 24) as a term for something of great rarity.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] The idiom later became common in many languages and appeared in Slavic folk tales.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In one such tale, the beautiful princess tests the ardor and resourcefulness of her suitor by sending him out into the wilderness to find and bring back the one fantastical luxury she does not have: bird's milk.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In the fairy tale *Little Hare* by Aleksey Remizov (who wrote many imitations of traditional Slavic folk tales), the magic bird Gagana produces milk.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Whether any of these authors were aware of crop milk from some species of birds is unknown.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Bird's milk was first created in 1936 in Poland by Jan Wedel, owner of the E.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Wedel Chocolate Factory Museum in Warsaw, dedicated to the history of chocolate-making and the Wedel brand.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] The museum includes a dedicated room devoted entirely to Ptasie Mleczko, where visitors can design their own packaging for the candy.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In Russia, *ptichye moloko* was originally a type of confectionery introduced in 1967 in Vladivostok and in 1968 by the Rot Front factory in Moscow.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] It became a hit, and mass production was started in 1975 by the *Krasny Oktyabr* confectionery factory in Moscow.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In Estonia, *linnupiim* (also bird's milk in Estonian) is the brand name of a similar candy made by the Kalev candy factory.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] This candy also uses agar-agar instead of gelatin as a thickening agent and comes in three flavors: chocolate, vanilla, and lemon.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In 2021, a special edition with grapefruit flavor was produced.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In Moldova, *lapte de pasăre* (also bird's milk in Romanian) is the brand name of a similar candy made by the Bucuria candy factory.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Despite the name, the candy is not to be confused with the Romanian traditional dessert *lapte de pasăre*.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In Lithuania, *paukščių pienas* (also bird's milk in Lithuanian) is the brand name of a similar candy made by the Vilniaus Pergalė factory.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In 1978, the popular candy was transformed into a cake by Vladimir Guralnik in Moscow's Praga Restaurant.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] This was a light sponge cake filled with an airy soufflé and topped with chocolate glaze.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] A distinct feature of the Russian recipe is the usage of agar-agar instead of gelatin as a thickening agent, which withstands the high temperature needed to melt down sugar into a syrup.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Initially, the restaurant produced trial batches of 20–30 cakes, but after six months the daily output was increased to 500 cakes.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] The recipe was quickly copied by other restaurants in Moscow, such as Moskva, Budapesht, and Ukraina.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In the 1980s, a special factory for Bird's milk cakes was built in the Novye Cheryomushky district in the south of Moscow.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Both the cake and the candy versions of the bird's milk are widely available to this date in supermarkets and specialty stores all over Russia.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] In Russia, *Птичье молоко* is a registered trademark of Rot Front, a member of United Confectioners.
[src:bird-s-milk/bird-s-milk] Other companies have been sued for using the name, even if they had used it in the Soviet Union.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English is either the official language, or one of the official languages, of 57 sovereign states and 30 dependent territories, making it the most geographically widespread language in the world.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In the United Kingdom, the United States, Australia, and New Zealand, it is the dominant language for historical reasons without being explicitly defined by law.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] It is a co‑official language of the United Nations, the European Union, and many other international and regional organisations.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] It has also become the *de facto* lingua franca of diplomacy, science, technology, international trade, logistics, tourism, aviation, entertainment, and the Internet.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] *Ethnologue* estimated that there were over 1.4 billion speakers worldwide as of 2021.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Old English emerged from a group of West Germanic dialects spoken by the Anglo-Saxons.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Early inscriptions were written with runes before a Latin‑based alphabet was adopted for longer texts.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Late Old English borrowed some grammar and core vocabulary from Old Norse, a North Germanic language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] An evolution of the Latin alphabet, the English alphabet, fully supplanted the runic alphabet by the High Middle Ages, coinciding with the emergence of Middle English in England under Norman control.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Middle English borrowed vocabulary extensively from French dialects, which are the source of approximately 28 per cent of Modern English words, and from Latin, which is the source of an additional 28 per cent.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] While Latin and the Romance languages are thus the source for a majority of its lexicon taken as a whole, English's grammar and phonology remain Germanic, as does most of its basic everyday vocabulary.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Finally, Middle English transformed, in part through the Great Vowel Shift, into Modern English, which exists on a dialect continuum with Scots; it is next most closely related to Low Saxon and Frisian.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English is a member of the Indo-European language family, belonging to the West Germanic branch of Germanic languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Old English was one of several Ingvaeonic languages, which emerged from a dialect continuum spoken by West Germanic peoples during the 5th century in Frisia, on the coast of the North Sea.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Old English emerged among the Ingvaeonic speakers on the British Isles following their migration to the region, while the other Ingvaeonic languages (Frisian and Old Low German) developed in parallel on the European continent.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Old English evolved into Middle English, which in turn evolved into Modern English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Particular dialects of Old and Middle English also developed into other Anglic languages, including Scots and the extinct Fingallian and Yola dialects of Ireland.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English was isolated from other Germanic languages on the continent and diverged considerably in vocabulary, syntax, and phonology as a result.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] It is not mutually intelligible with any continental Germanic language – though some, such as Dutch and Frisian, share strong affinities with it, particularly in its earlier stages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English and Frisian were traditionally considered more closely related to one another than they were to other West Germanic languages, but most modern scholarship does not recognise a particular affinity between them.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Though they shared similar sound changes that were found nowhere else around the North Sea at that time, the specific changes appeared in English and Frisian at different times – a pattern that is uncharacteristic of languages that share a unique phylogenetic ancestor.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Old English (also called *Anglo-Saxon*) was the earliest form of the English language, spoken from c.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Old English developed from a set of West Germanic dialects, sometimes identified as Anglo-Frisian or North Sea Germanic, originally spoken along the coasts of Frisia, Lower Saxony and southern Jutland by the Germanic peoples known from historical records as the Angles, Saxons, and Jutes.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] From the 5th century, the Anglo-Saxons settled Britain as the Roman economy and administration collapsed.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] By the 7th century, Old English had become dominant in Britain – replacing the Common Brittonic and British Latin previously spoken during the Roman occupation, which left little influence on English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] *England* and *English* (originally *Ænglaland* and *Ænglisc*) are both named after the Angles.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Old English was divided into two Anglian dialects (Mercian and Northumbrian) and two Saxon dialects (Kentish and West Saxon).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Through the influence of the kingdom of Wessex and the educational reforms instated by King Alfred during the 9th century, the West Saxon dialect became the standard written variety.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The epic poem *Beowulf* is written in West Saxon, and the earliest English poem, *Cædmon's Hymn*, is written in Northumbrian.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Modern English developed mainly from Mercian, but the Scots language developed from Northumbrian.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] During the earliest period of Old English, a few short inscriptions were made using a runic alphabet.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] By the 7th century, a Latin alphabet had been adopted.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Written with half-uncial letterforms, it included the runic letters *wynn* ⟨*ƿ*⟩ and *thorn* ⟨*þ*⟩, and the modified Latin letters *eth* ⟨*ð*⟩ and *ash* ⟨*æ*⟩.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Old English is markedly different from Modern English; 21st‑century English speakers are entirely unable to understand Old English without special training.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Its grammar was similar to that of modern German: nouns, adjectives, pronouns, and verbs had many more inflectional endings and forms, and word order was much freer than in Modern English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Modern English has case forms in pronouns (*he*, *him*, *his*) and a few verb inflections (*speak*, *speaks*, *speaking*, *spoke*, *spoken*), but Old English had case endings in nouns as well, and verbs had more person and number endings.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Between the 8th and 11th centuries, the English spoken in some regions underwent significant changes due to contact with Old Norse, a North Germanic language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Several waves of Norsemen colonising the northern British Isles in the 8th and 9th centuries brought Old English speakers into constant contact with Old Norse.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Norse influence was strongest in the north‑eastern varieties of Old English spoken in the Danelaw surrounding York; today these features are still particularly evident in Scots and Northern English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The centre of Norse influence was Lindsey, located in the Midlands.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] After Lindsey was incorporated into the Anglo‑Saxon polity in 920, English spread extensively throughout the region.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] One element of Norse influence that persists in all English varieties today is the third‑person pronoun group beginning with *th-* (*they*, *them*, *their*), which replaced the Anglo‑Saxon pronouns with *h-* (*hie, him, hera*).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Other Norse loanwords include *give*, *get*, *sky*, *skirt*, *egg*, and *cake*, typically displacing a native Anglo‑Saxon equivalent.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Old Norse in this era remained largely mutually intelligible with some dialects of Old English, particularly northern ones.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The Middle English period is often defined as beginning with the Norman Conquest in 1066.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] During the centuries that followed, English was heavily influenced by the form of Old French spoken by the new Norman ruling class that had migrated to England (known as Old Norman).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Over the following decades of contact, members of the middle and upper classes, whether native English or Norman, became increasingly bilingual.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] By 1150 at the latest, bilingual speakers represented a majority of the English aristocracy, and monolingual French speakers were nearly non‑existent.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The French spoken by the Norman elite in England eventually developed into the Anglo‑Norman language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The transition from Old to Middle English can also be placed during the composition of the *Ormulum* (c. late 12th century), a work by the Augustinian canon Orrm which highlights the blending of Old English and Anglo‑Norman elements in the language for the first time.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] As the lower classes, who represented the vast majority of the population, remained monolingual English speakers, the primary influence of Norman was as a lexical superstratum, introducing a wide range of loanwords related to politics, legislation, and prestigious social domains.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] For instance, the French word *trône* appears for the first time, from which the English word *throne* is derived.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Middle English also greatly simplified the inflectional system, probably in order to reconcile Old Norse and Old English, which were inflectionally different but morphologically similar.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The distinction between nominative and accusative cases was lost except in personal pronouns; the instrumental case was dropped; and the use of the genitive case was limited to indicating possession.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The inflectional system regularised many irregular inflectional forms, and gradually simplified the system of agreement, making word order less flexible.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Middle English literature includes Geoffrey Chaucer's *Canterbury Tales* (c.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] During the Middle English period, the use of regional dialects in writing proliferated, and dialect traits were even used for effect by authors such as Chaucer.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In the first translation of the entire Bible into English by John Wycliffe (1382), Matthew 8:20 reads: "Foxis han dennes, and briddis of heuene han nestis." Here the plural suffix *-n* on the verb *have* is still retained, but none of the case endings on the nouns are present.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The period of Early Modern English, lasting from 1500 to 1700, was characterised by the Great Vowel Shift (1350–1700), inflectional simplification, and linguistic standardisation.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The Great Vowel Shift affected the stressed long vowels of Middle English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] It was a chain shift, meaning that each shift triggered a subsequent shift in the vowel system.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Mid and open vowels were raised, and close vowels were broken into diphthongs.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] For example, the word *bite* was originally pronounced as the word *beet* is today, and the second vowel in the word *about* was pronounced as the word *boot* is today.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The Great Vowel Shift explains many irregularities in spelling, since English retains many spellings from Middle English, and it also explains why English vowel letters have very different pronunciations from the same letters in other languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English began to rise in prestige relative to Norman French during the reign of Henry V.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Around 1430, the Court of Chancery in Westminster began using English in its official documents, and a new standard form of Middle English, known as Chancery Standard, developed from the dialects of London and the East Midlands.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In 1476, William Caxton introduced the printing press to England and began publishing the first printed books in London, thereby expanding the influence of this form of English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Literature in Early Modern English includes the works of William Shakespeare and the 1611 King James Version (KJV) of the Bible.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Even after the vowel shift, the language still sounded different from Modern English: for example, the consonant clusters /kn ɡn sw/ in *knight*, *gnat*, and *sword* were still pronounced.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Many of the grammatical features that a modern reader of Shakespeare might find quaint or archaic represent the distinct characteristics of Early Modern English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] By the late 18th century, the British Empire had spread English through its colonies and geopolitical dominance.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Commerce, science and technology, diplomacy, art, and formal education all contributed to English becoming the first truly global language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English also facilitated worldwide international communication.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English was adopted in parts of North America, parts of Africa, Oceania, and many other regions.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] When they obtained political independence, some of the newly independent states that had multiple indigenous languages opted to continue using English as the official language, in order to avoid the political and other difficulties inherent in promoting any one indigenous language above the others.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In the 20th century, the growing economic and cultural influence of the United States and its status as a superpower following the Second World War – along with worldwide broadcasting in English by the BBC and other broadcasters – has caused the language to spread across the planet much faster.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In 1951, the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) recommended to the International Chicago Convention that Aviation English be universally adopted for "international aeronautical radiotelephony communications".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In 2001, the International Maritime Organization (IMO) developed a set of key phrases, named Standard Marine Communication Phrases (SMCP), in English, to be the recognised language supported by the international maritime community for use at sea.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In the 21st century, English is more widely spoken and written than any other language in history.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] As Modern English developed, explicit norms for standard usage were published and spread through official media such as public education and state‑sponsored publications.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In 1755, Samuel Johnson published his *Dictionary of the English Language*, which introduced standard spellings of words and usage norms.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In 1828, Noah Webster published the *American Dictionary of the English Language* to establish a norm for speaking and writing American English independent of the British standard.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Within Britain, non‑standard or lower‑class dialect features were increasingly stigmatised, leading to the rapid spread of the prestige varieties among the middle classes.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In modern English, the loss of grammatical case is almost complete (it is now found only in pronouns, such as *he* and *him*, *she* and *her*, *who* and *whom*), and subject–verb–object word order is largely fixed.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Some changes, such as the use of *do*-support, have become universalised.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] (Earlier English did not use the word *do* as a general auxiliary as Modern English does; at first it was used only in question constructions, and even then it was not obligatory.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Now, *do*-support with the verb *have* is becoming increasingly standardised.) The use of progressive forms ending in *-ing* appears to be spreading to new constructions, and forms such as "had been being built" are becoming more common.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Regularisation of irregular forms also continues slowly (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] *dreamed* instead of *dreamt*), and analytical alternatives to inflectional forms are becoming more common (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] British English is also undergoing change under the influence of American English, fuelled by the strong presence of American English in the media.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] As of 2016, 400 million people spoke English as their first language, and 1.1 billion spoke it as a second language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English is the largest language by number of speakers, spoken by communities on every continent.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Estimates of second‑language and foreign‑language speakers vary greatly depending on how proficiency is defined, ranging from 470 million to more than 1 billion.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In 2003, David Crystal estimated that non‑native speakers outnumbered native speakers by a ratio of three to one.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Braj Kachru has categorised countries into the Three Circles of English model, according to how the language historically spread in each country, how it is acquired by the population, and the range of uses it has there – with a country's classification being able to change over time.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] 'Inner‑circle' countries have large communities of native English speakers; these include the United Kingdom, the United States, Australia, Canada, Ireland, and New Zealand (where the majority speaks English), as well as South Africa (where a significant minority speaks English).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The countries with the most native English speakers are, in descending order: the United States (at least 231 million), the United Kingdom (60 million), Canada (19 million), Australia (at least 17 million), South Africa (4.8 million), Ireland (4.2 million), and New Zealand (3.7 million).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In these countries, children of native speakers learn English from their parents; citizens with other first languages, as well as incoming immigrants, learn English in order to communicate in local English‑speaking neighbourhoods and workplaces.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Inner‑circle countries are the base from which English spreads to other regions of the world.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] These countries have millions of native speakers on dialect continua, which range from English-based creole languages to standard varieties of English used in inner‑circle countries.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] They have many more speakers who acquire English as they grow up through day‑to‑day use and exposure to English‑language broadcasting, especially if they attend schools where English is the language of instruction.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] 'Expanding‑circle' countries are those where English is taught as a foreign language, though the character of English as a first, second, or foreign language in a given country is often debatable and may change over time.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] For example, in countries such as the Netherlands, an overwhelming majority of the population can speak English, and it is often used in higher education and to communicate with foreigners.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English is a pluricentric language, which means that no single national authority sets the standard for its use.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Spoken English, including English used in broadcasting, generally follows national pronunciation standards that are established by custom rather than by regulation.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] International broadcasters are usually identifiable as coming from one country rather than another through their accents, but newsreader scripts are also composed largely in international standard written English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The norms of standard written English are maintained purely by the consensus of educated English speakers around the world, without any oversight by any government or international organisation.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] American listeners readily understand most British broadcasting, and British listeners readily understand most American broadcasting.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Most English speakers around the world can understand radio programmes, television programmes, and films from many parts of the English-speaking world.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Both standard and non‑standard varieties of English can include formal or informal styles, distinguished by word choice and syntax, and they use both technical and non‑technical registers.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The settlement history of the English‑speaking inner‑circle countries outside Britain helped to level dialect distinctions and produce koiné forms of English in South Africa, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The majority of immigrants to the United States without British ancestry rapidly adopted English after arrival.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Now the majority of the United States population are monolingual English speakers.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Modern English is sometimes described as the first global lingua franca, or as the first world language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English is the world's most widely used language in newspaper publishing, book publishing, international telecommunications, scientific publishing, international trade, mass entertainment, and diplomacy.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Parity with French as a language of diplomacy had been achieved by the Treaty of Versailles negotiations in 1919.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] By the time the United Nations was founded at the end of the Second World War, English had become pre‑eminent; it is one of the six official languages of the United Nations and is now the main worldwide language of diplomacy and international relations.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Many other worldwide international organisations, including the International Olympic Committee, specify English as a working language or official language of the organisation.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] While the EU allows member states to designate any of the national languages as an official language of the Union, in practice English is the main working language of EU organisations.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English serves as the basis for the required controlled natural languages Seaspeak and Airspeak, used as international languages of seafaring and aviation.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English is the most frequently taught foreign language in the world.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Most people learning English do so for practical reasons, as opposed to ideological ones.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In EU countries, English is the most widely spoken foreign language in 19 of the 25 member states where it is not an official language (that is, the countries other than Ireland and Malta).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In a 2012 official Eurobarometer poll (conducted when the UK was still a member of the EU), 38 per cent of EU respondents outside the countries where English is an official language said they could speak English well enough to have a conversation in that language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The next most commonly mentioned foreign language, French (which is the most widely known foreign language in the UK and Ireland), could be used in conversation by 12 per cent of respondents.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Working knowledge of English has become a requirement in a number of occupations and professions, such as medicine and computing.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Though it formerly had parity with French and German in scientific research, English now dominates the field.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] As decolonisation proceeded throughout the British Empire in the 1950s and 1960s, former colonies often did not reject English but rather continued to use it as independent countries setting their own language policies.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] For example, English is one of the official languages of India.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Many Indians have shifted from associating the language with colonialism to associating it with economic progress.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English is widely used in media and literature, with India being the third‑largest publisher of English‑language books in the world, after the US and the UK.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] However, fewer than 5 per cent of the population speak English fluently, with the country's native English speakers numbering in the low hundreds of thousands.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In 2004, David Crystal claimed that India had the largest population of people able to speak or understand English in the world, though most scholars estimate that the US remains home to a larger English‑speaking population.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Many English speakers in Africa have become part of an 'Afro‑Saxon' language community that unites Africans from different countries.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Regarding its future development, it is considered most likely that English will continue to function as a koiné language, with a standard form that unifies speakers around the world.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Dialectologists identify many English dialects, which usually refer to regional varieties that differ from each other in terms of patterns of grammar, vocabulary, and pronunciation.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The pronunciation of particular areas distinguishes dialects as separate regional accents.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The major native dialects of English are often divided by linguists into two extremely general categories: British English (BrE) and North American English (NAE).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The fact that English has been spoken in England for 1,500 years explains why England has a great wealth of regional dialects.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Within the United Kingdom, Received Pronunciation (RP), an educated accent associated originally with South East England, has been traditionally used as a broadcast standard and is considered the most prestigious of British accents.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The spread of RP (also known as BBC English) through the media has caused many traditional dialects of rural England to recede, as youths adopt the traits of the prestige variety instead of those from local dialects.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] At the time of the 1950–61 Survey of English Dialects, grammar and vocabulary differed across the country, but a process of lexical attrition has led most of this variation to disappear.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Nonetheless, this attrition has mostly affected dialectal variation in grammar and vocabulary.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Only 3% of the English population actually speak RP, with the remainder speaking in regional accents and dialects with varying degrees of RP influence.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] There is also variability within RP, particularly along class lines between upper‑ and middle‑class RP speakers, and between native RP speakers and those who adopt RP later in life.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Within Britain, there is also considerable variation along lines of social class; some traits, though exceedingly common, are nonetheless considered 'non‑standard' and associated with lower‑class speakers and identities.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] An example of this is *h*-dropping, which was historically a feature of lower‑class London English, particularly Cockney, and can now be heard in the local accents of most parts of England.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] However, it remains largely absent from broadcasting and among the upper crust of British society.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English in England can be divided into four major dialect regions: South East English, South West English (also known as West Country English), Midlands English, and Northern English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Having been the centre of Danish occupation during the Viking invasions of England, Northern English dialects, particularly the Yorkshire dialect, retain Norse features not found in other English varieties.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In the West Midlands, dialects such as Black Country (Yam Yam), and to a lesser extent Birmingham (Brummie), preserve archaic features from Early Modern and Middle English, retaining Germanic elements such as specific grammatical structures and vocabulary.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Since the 15th century, South East England varieties have centred on London, which has been the centre from which dialectal innovations have spread to other dialects.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In London, the Cockney dialect was traditionally used by the lower classes, and it was long a socially stigmatised variety.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The spread of Cockney features across the South East led the media to talk of Estuary English as a new dialect, but the notion was criticised by many linguists on the grounds that London had been influencing neighbouring regions throughout history.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Scots is today considered a separate language from English, but it has its origins in early Northern Middle English and developed and changed during its history with influence from other sources, particularly Scottish Gaelic and Old Norse.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Scots itself has a number of regional dialects.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In addition to Scots, Scottish English comprises the varieties of Standard English spoken in Scotland; most varieties are Northern English accents, with some influence from Scots.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In Ireland, various forms of English have been spoken following the Norman invasion of the island during the 11th century.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In County Wexford and the area surrounding Dublin, two extinct dialects known as Forth and Bargy and Fingallian developed as offshoots from Early Middle English and were spoken until the 19th century.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Modern Irish English, however, has its roots in English colonisation in the 17th century.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Today Irish English is divided into Ulster English (the Northern Ireland dialect with strong influence from Scots) and various other dialects of Ireland.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Like Scottish and most North American accents, almost all Irish accents preserve the rhoticity that has been lost in the dialects influenced by RP.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Due to the relatively strong degree of mixing, mutual accommodation, and koinéisation that occurred during the colonial period, North American English has traditionally been perceived as relatively homogeneous, at least in comparison with British dialects.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] However, modern scholars have strongly opposed this notion, arguing that North American English shows a great deal of phonetic, lexical, and geographic variability.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] This becomes all the more apparent considering social, ethnolinguistic, and regional varieties such as African-American English, Chicano English, Cajun English, or Newfoundland English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Canadian English varieties, excepting those from Atlantic Canada and possibly Quebec, are generally considered to belong to the GA continuum, although they often show raising of the vowels /aɪ/ and /aʊ/ before voiceless consonants and have distinct norms for writing and pronunciation as well.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Atlantic Canadian English, notably distinct from Standard Canadian English, comprises Maritime English and Newfoundland English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] It was influenced mostly by British and Irish English, as well as Irish, Scottish Gaelic, and Acadian French.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In most American and Canadian English dialects, rhoticity (or *r*-fullness) is dominant, with non-rhoticity (or *r*-dropping) being associated with lower prestige and social class, especially since the end of World War II.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] This contrasts with the situation in England, where non-rhoticity has become the standard.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Varieties beyond GA which have developed distinct sound systems include the Southern American English, New York City English, Eastern New England English, and African-American Vernacular English (AAVE) groups – all of which are historically non-rhotic, save a few varieties of Southern American.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In Southern American English, the most populous grouping outside GA, rhoticity now strongly prevails, replacing the region's historical non-rhotic prestige.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Spoken primarily by working- and middle-class African Americans, African-American Vernacular English (AAVE) is largely non-rhotic, and likely originated among enslaved Africans and African Americans influenced primarily by the non-standard older Southern dialects.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] A minority of linguists, contrarily, propose that AAVE mostly traces back to African languages spoken by the slaves who had to develop a pidgin or English-based creole to communicate with slaves of other ethnic and linguistic origins.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] AAVE's important commonalities with Southern accents suggest it developed into a highly coherent and homogeneous variety in the 19th or early 20th century.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] AAVE is commonly stigmatised in North America as a form of "broken" or "uneducated" English, as are white Southern accents, but linguists today recognise both as fully developed varieties of English with their own norms shared by large speech communities.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Since 1788, English has been spoken in Oceania, and Australian English has developed as the first language of the vast majority of the inhabitants of the Australian continent, its standard accent being General Australian.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The English of neighbouring New Zealand has, to a lesser degree, become an influential standard variety of the language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Australian and New Zealand English are each other's closest relatives, with few differentiating characteristics, followed by South African English and the English of South East England, all of which have similarly non‑rhotic accents (aside from some accents in the South Island of New Zealand).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Australian and New Zealand English stand out for their innovative vowels: many short vowels are fronted or raised, whereas many long vowels have been diphthongised.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Australian English also has a contrast between long and short vowels that is not found in most other varieties.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Australian English grammar aligns closely with British and American English; like American English, collective plural subjects take a singular verb – for example, "the government is" (rather than 'are').
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] New Zealand English uses front vowels that are often even higher than those in Australian English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English is an official language of the Philippines.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Its use is ubiquitous in the country, appearing on street signs, marquees, and government documents, as well as in courtrooms, public media, the entertainment industry, and the business sector.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] It became an important and widely spoken language in the country during the period of American rule between 1898 and 1946.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Taglish is a prominent form of code-switching between Tagalog and English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] English is spoken widely in southern Africa and is an official or co‑official language in several of the region's countries.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In South Africa, English has been spoken since 1820, co‑existing with Afrikaans and various African languages such as the Khoe and Bantu languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Today, about nine per cent of the South African population speaks South African English (SAE) as a first language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] SAE is a non‑rhotic variety that tends to follow RP as a norm.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] It is one of the few non‑rhotic English varieties that lack intrusive R.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The second‑language varieties of South Africa differ according to the native languages of their speakers.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Most phonological differences from RP are in the vowels.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Consonantal differences include the tendency to pronounce /p, t, t͡ʃ, k/ without aspiration (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] *pin* pronounced [pɪn] rather than [pʰɪn] as in most other varieties), while 'r' is often pronounced as a flap [ɾ] instead of as the more common fricative.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Nigerian English is a variety of English spoken in Nigeria; over 150 million Nigerians speak some form of the language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Though traditionally based on British English, increasing United States influence during the latter part of the 20th century has resulted in American English vocabulary entering Nigerian English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Additionally, some new words and collocations have emerged from the variety out of a need to express concepts specific to the nation's culture (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Varieties of English are spoken throughout the former British colonial possessions in the Caribbean, including Jamaica, the Leeward and Windward Islands, Trinidad and Tobago, Barbados, the Cayman Islands, and Belize.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Each of these areas is home both to a local variety of English and a local English‑based creole, combining English and African languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The most prominent varieties are Jamaican English and Jamaican Creole.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] In Central America, English‑based creoles are spoken on the Caribbean coasts of Nicaragua and Panama.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Residents are often fluent in both the local English variety and the local creole languages, and frequently code-switch between them.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The relationship between different varieties can be conceptualised as a continuum, in which more creole‑like or RP‑like forms function as more formal and informal registers of the language respectively.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Most Caribbean varieties are based on British English and, consequently, most are non‑rhotic, except for formal styles of Jamaican English, which are often rhotic.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Jamaican English differs from RP in its vowel inventory, which has a distinction between long and short vowels rather than tense and lax vowels as in Standard English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] The diphthongs /ei/ and /ou/ are monophthongs [eː] and [oː] or even the reverse diphthongs [ie] and [uo] (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] *bay* and *boat* pronounced [bʲeː] and [bʷoːt]).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Often, word‑final consonant clusters are simplified so that "child" is pronounced [t͡ʃail] and "wind" [win].
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Indian English historically tends towards RP as an ideal, with the proximity of speakers to RP generally reflecting class distinctions.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Indian English accents are marked by the pronunciation of phonemes such as /t/ and /d/ (often pronounced with retroflex articulation as [ʈ] and [ɖ]) and the replacement of /θ/ and /ð/ with dentals [t̪] and [d̪].
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Sometimes Indian English speakers may also use spelling‑based pronunciations, where the silent ⟨h⟩ found in words such as *ghost* is pronounced as an Indian voiced aspirated stop [ɡʱ].
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] Non‑native English speakers may pronounce words differently because they have not fully mastered English pronunciation.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] This can happen either because they apply the speech rules of their mother tongue to English ('interference') or because they implement strategies similar to those used in first language acquisition.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p01] They may create novel pronunciations for English sounds that do not exist in their first language.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English phonology and phonetics differ from one dialect to another, usually without interfering with mutual communication.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Phonological variation affects the inventory of phonemes (speech sounds that distinguish meaning), and phonetic variation consists in differences in pronunciation of the phonemes.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] This overview mainly describes Received Pronunciation (RP) and General American (GA), the standard varieties of the United Kingdom and the United States respectively.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Most English dialects share the same 24 consonant phonemes (or 26, if marginal /x/ and glottal stop /ʔ/ are included).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The consonant inventory shown below is valid for California English, and for RP.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For pairs of obstruents (stops, affricates, and fricatives) such as /p b/, /tʃ dʒ/, and /s z/, the first is fortis (strong) and the second is lenis (weak).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Fortis obstruents, such as /p tʃ s/ are pronounced with more muscular tension and breath force than lenis consonants, such as /b dʒ z/, and are always voiceless.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Lenis consonants are partly voiced at the beginning and end of utterances, and fully voiced between vowels.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Fortis stops such as /p/ have additional articulatory or acoustic features in most dialects: they are aspirated [pʰ] when they occur alone at the beginning of a stressed syllable, often unaspirated in other cases, and often unreleased [p̚] or pre-glottalised [ʔp] at the end of a syllable.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In a single-syllable word, a vowel before a fortis stop is shortened: e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] *nip* has a noticeably shorter vowel (phonetically, not phonemically) than *nib* [nɪˑb̥] (see below).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In RP, the lateral approximant /l/ has two main allophones (pronunciation variants): the clear or plain [l], as in *light*, and the dark or velarised [ɫ], as in *full*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] All sonorants (liquids /l, r/ and nasals /m, n, ŋ/) devoice when following a voiceless obstruent, and they are syllabic when following a consonant at the end of a word.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The pronunciation of vowels varies a great deal between dialects and is one of the most detectable aspects of a speaker's accent.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The accompanying table below lists the vowel phonemes in RP and GA, with example words from lexical sets.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The vowels are represented with symbols from the International Phonetic Alphabet; those given for RP are standard in British dictionaries and other publications.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In RP, vowel length is phonemic; long vowels are marked with a triangular colon ⟨ː⟩ in the table above, such as the vowel of *need* [niːd] as opposed to *bid* [bɪd].
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Because lenis consonants are frequently voiceless at the end of a syllable, vowel length is an important cue as to whether the following consonant is lenis or fortis.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The vowel /ə/ only occurs in unstressed syllables and is more open in quality in stem-final positions.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Some dialects do not contrast /ɪ/ and /ə/ in unstressed positions, such that *rabbit* and *abbot* rhyme and *Lenin* and *Lennon* are homophonous, a dialectal feature called the weak vowel merger.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] GA /ɜr/ and /ər/ are realised as an *r*-coloured vowel [ɚ], as in *further* [ˈfɚðɚ] (phonemically /ˈfɜrðər/), which in RP is realised as [ˈfəːðə] (phonemically /ˈfɜːðə/).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] An English syllable includes a syllable nucleus consisting of a vowel sound.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Syllable onset and coda (start and end) are optional.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] A syllable can start with up to three consonant sounds, as in *sprint* /sprɪnt/, and end with up to five, as in (for some dialects) *angsts* /aŋksts/.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] This gives an English syllable a structure of (CCC)V(CCCCC) – where C represents a consonant and V a vowel.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The word *strengths* /strɛŋθs/ is thus close to the most complex syllable possible in English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The consonants that may appear together in onsets or codas are restricted, as is the order in which they may appear.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Onsets can only have four types of consonant clusters: a stop and approximant, as in *play*; a voiceless fricative and approximant, as in *fly* or *sly*; *s* and a voiceless stop, as in *stay*; and *s*, a voiceless stop, and an approximant, as in *string*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Clusters of nasal and stop are only allowed in codas.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Clusters of obstruents always agree in voicing, and clusters of sibilants and of plosives with the same point of articulation are prohibited.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Several consonants have limited distributions: /h/ can only occur in syllable-initial position, and /ŋ/ only in syllable-final position.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Stress plays an important role in English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Certain syllables are stressed, while others are unstressed.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Stress is a combination of duration, intensity, vowel quality, and sometimes changes in pitch.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Stressed syllables are pronounced longer and louder than unstressed syllables, and vowels in unstressed syllables are frequently reduced while vowels in stressed syllables are not.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Stress in English is phonemic, gaining freedom and dynamicity once lost in Proto-Germanic through a majority of borrowings from non-Germanic languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For instance, the word *contract* is stressed on the first syllable (/ˈkɒntrækt/ *KON-trakt*) when used as a noun, but on the last syllable (/kənˈtrækt/ *kən-TRAKT*) for most meanings (for example, "reduce in size") when used as a verb.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Here stress is connected to vowel reduction: in the noun "contract" the first syllable is stressed and has the unreduced vowel /ɒ/, but in the verb "contract" the first syllable is unstressed and its vowel is reduced to /ə/.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Stress is also used to distinguish between words and phrases, so that a compound word receives a single stress unit, but the corresponding phrase has two: e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "a burnout" (/ˈbɜːrnaʊt/) versus "to burn out" (/ˈbɜːrn ˈaʊt/), and "a hotdog" (/ˈhɒtdɒɡ/) versus "a hot dog" (/ˈhɒt ˈdɒɡ/).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In terms of rhythm, English is generally described as a stress-timed language, meaning that the amount of time between stressed syllables tends to be equal.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Stressed syllables are pronounced longer, but unstressed syllables (syllables between stresses) are shortened.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Vowels in unstressed syllables are shortened as well, and vowel shortening causes changes in vowel quality: vowel reduction.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Varieties of English vary the most in pronunciation of vowels.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The best-known national varieties used as standards for education in non-English-speaking countries are British (BrE) and American (AmE).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Countries such as Canada, Australia, Ireland, New Zealand and South Africa have their own standard varieties which are less often used as standards for education internationally.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English has undergone many historical sound changes, some of them affecting all varieties, and others affecting only a few.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Most standard varieties are affected by the Great Vowel Shift, which changed the pronunciation of long vowels, but a few dialects have slightly different results.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In North America, a number of chain shifts such as the Northern Cities Vowel Shift and Canadian Shift have produced very different vowel landscapes in some regional accents.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Some dialects have fewer or more consonant phonemes and phones than the standard varieties.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Some conservative varieties like Scottish English have a voiceless [ʍ] sound in *whine* that contrasts with the voiced [w] in *wine*, but most other dialects pronounce both words with voiced [w], a dialect feature called *wine*–*whine* merger.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The voiceless velar fricative sound /x/ is found in Scottish English, which distinguishes *loch* /lɔx/ from *lock* /lɔk/.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Other changes affecting the phonology of local varieties are processes such as *yod*-dropping, *yod*-coalescence, and reduction of consonant clusters.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] GA and RP vary in their pronunciation of historical /r/ after a vowel at the end of a syllable (in the syllable coda).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] GA is a rhotic dialect, meaning that it pronounces /r/ at the end of a syllable, but RP is non-rhotic, meaning that it loses /r/ in that position.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English dialects are classified as rhotic or non-rhotic depending on whether they elide /r/ like RP or keep it like GA.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] There is complex dialectal variation in words with the open front and open back vowels /æ ɑː ɒ ɔː/.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] These four vowels are only distinguished in RP, Australia, New Zealand and South Africa.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In GA, these vowels merge to three /æ ɑ ɔ/, and in Canadian English, they merge to two /æ ɑ/.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Since the 9th century, English has been written using the English alphabet, which uses the Latin script.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Anglo-Saxon runes were previously used to write Old English, but only in short inscriptions; the overwhelming majority of attested writings in Old English are in the Old English Latin alphabet.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English orthography is multi-layered and complex, with elements of French, Latin, and Greek spelling on top of the native Germanic system.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Further complications have arisen through sound changes with which the orthography has not kept pace.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Compared to European languages for which official organisations have promoted spelling reforms, English has spelling that is a less consistent indicator of pronunciation, and standard spellings of words that are more difficult to guess from knowing how a word is pronounced.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] There are also systematic spelling differences between British and American English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] These situations have prompted proposals for spelling reform in English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Although letters and speech sounds do not have a one-to-one correspondence in standard English spelling, spelling rules that take into account syllable structure, phonetic changes in derived words, and word accent are reliable for most English words.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Moreover, standard English spelling shows etymological relationships between related words that would be obscured by a closer correspondence between pronunciation and spelling – for example, the words *photograph*, *photography*, and *photographic*, or the words *electricity* and *electrical*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] While few scholars agree with Chomsky and Halle (1968) that conventional English orthography is "near-optimal", there is a rationale for current English spelling patterns.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The standard orthography of English is the most widely used writing system in the world.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Standard English spelling is based on a graphomorphemic segmentation of words into written clues of what meaningful units make up each word.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Readers of English can generally rely on the correspondence between spelling and pronunciation to be fairly regular for letters or digraphs used to spell consonant sounds.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The letters *c* and *g* normally represent /k/ and /ɡ/, but there is also a soft *c* pronounced /s/, and a soft *g* pronounced /dʒ/.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The differences in the pronunciations of the letters *c* and *g* are often signalled by the following letters in standard English spelling.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Digraphs used to represent phonemes and phoneme sequences include *ch* for /tʃ/, *sh* for /ʃ/, *th* for /θ/ or /ð/, *ng* for /ŋ/, *qu* for /kw/, and *ph* for /f/ in Greek-derived words.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The single letter *x* is generally pronounced as /z/ in word-initial position and as /ks/ otherwise.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For the vowel sounds of the English language, however, correspondences between spelling and pronunciation are more irregular.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] There are many more vowel phonemes in English than there are single vowel letters (*a*, *e*, *i*, *o*, *u*, *y*, and very rarely *w*).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] As a result, some "long vowels" are often indicated by combinations of letters (like the *oa* in *boat*, the *ow* in *how*, and the *ay* in *stay*), or the historically based silent *e* (as in *note* and *cake*).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The consequence of this complex orthographic history is that learning to read and write can be challenging in English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] It can take longer for school pupils to become independently fluent readers of English than of many other languages, including Italian, Spanish, and German.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Nonetheless, there is an advantage for learners of English reading in learning the specific sound-symbol regularities that occur in the standard English spellings of commonly used words.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Such instruction greatly reduces the risk of children experiencing reading difficulties in English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Making primary school teachers more aware of the primacy of morpheme representation in English may help learners learn more efficiently to read and write English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English writing also includes a system of punctuation marks that is similar to those used in most alphabetic languages around the world.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The purpose of punctuation is to mark meaningful grammatical relationships in sentences to aid readers in understanding a text and to indicate features important for reading a text aloud.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Typical for an Indo-European language, English grammar follows accusative morphosyntactic alignment.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Unlike other Indo-European languages, English has largely abandoned the inflectional case system in favour of analytic constructions.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Only the personal pronouns retain morphological case more strongly than any other word class.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English distinguishes at least seven major word classes: verbs, nouns, adjectives, adverbs, determiners (including articles), prepositions, and conjunctions.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Some analyses add pronouns as a class separate from nouns, and subdivide conjunctions into subordinators and coordinators, and add the class of interjections.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English also has a rich set of auxiliary verbs, such as *have* and *do*, expressing the categories of mood and aspect.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Questions are marked by *do*-support, *wh*-movement (fronting of question words beginning with *wh*-) and word order inversion with some verbs.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Vestiges of the case and gender system are found in the pronoun system (*he* / *him*, *who* / *whom*); similarly, traces of more complex verb conjugation are seen in the inflection of the copula verb *to be*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English nouns are only inflected for number and possession.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] New nouns can be formed through derivation or compounding.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] They are semantically divided into proper nouns (names) and common nouns.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Common nouns are in turn divided into concrete and abstract nouns, and grammatically into count nouns and mass nouns.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Most count nouns are inflected for plural number through the use of the plural suffix -*s*, but a few nouns have irregular plural forms.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Mass nouns can only be pluralised through the use of a count noun classifier, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "one loaf of bread", "two loaves of bread".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Possession can be expressed either by the possessive enclitic -*s* (also traditionally called a genitive suffix), or by the preposition *of*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Historically the -*s* possessive has been used for animate nouns, whereas the *of* possessive has been reserved for inanimate nouns.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Today this distinction is less clear, and many speakers use -*s* also with inanimates.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Orthographically the possessive -*s* is separated from a singular noun with an apostrophe.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] If the noun is plural formed with -*s* the apostrophe follows the -*s*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Nouns can form noun phrases (NPs) where they are the syntactic head of the words that depend on them such as determiners, quantifiers, conjunctions or adjectives.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Noun phrases can be short, such as *the man*, composed only of a determiner and a noun.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] They can also include modifiers such as adjectives (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] *red*, *tall*, *all*) and specifiers such as determiners (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] But they can also tie together several nouns into a single long NP, using conjunctions such as *and*, or prepositions such as *with*, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "the tall man with the long red trousers and his skinny wife with the spectacles" (this NP uses conjunctions, prepositions, specifiers, and modifiers).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Regardless of length, an NP functions as a syntactic unit.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, the possessive enclitic can, in cases which do not lead to ambiguity, follow the entire noun phrase, as in "The President of India's wife", where the enclitic follows *India* and not *President*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The class of determiners is used to specify the noun they precede in terms of definiteness, where *the* marks a definite noun and *a* or *an* marks an indefinite one.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] A definite noun is assumed by the speaker to be already known by the interlocutor, whereas an indefinite noun is not specified as being previously known.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Quantifiers, which include *one*, *many*, *some* and *all*, are used to specify the noun in terms of quantity or number.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The noun must agree with the number of the determiner, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Determiners are the first constituents in a noun phrase.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English adjectives are words such as *good*, *big*, *interesting*, and *Canadian* that most typically modify nouns, denoting characteristics of their referents (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] As modifiers, they come before the nouns they modify and after determiners.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English adjectives also function as predicative complements (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In Modern English, adjectives are not inflected so as to agree in form with the noun they modify, as in most other Indo-European languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrases "the slender boy", and "many slender girls", the adjective *slender* does not change form to agree with either the number or gender of the noun.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Some adjectives are inflected for degree of comparison, with the positive degree unmarked, the suffix -*er* marking the comparative, and -*est* marking the superlative: "a small boy", "the boy is smaller than the girl", "that boy is the smallest".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Some adjectives have irregular suppletive comparative and superlative forms, such as *good*, *better*, and *best*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Other adjectives have comparatives formed by periphrastic constructions, with the adverb *more* marking the comparative, and *most* marking the superlative: *happier* or *more happy*, *the happiest* or *most happy*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] There is some variation among speakers regarding which adjectives use inflected or periphrastic comparison, and some studies have shown a tendency for the periphrastic forms to become more common at the expense of the inflected form.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English determiners are words such as *the*, *each*, *many*, *some*, and *which*, occurring most typically in noun phrases before the head nouns and any modifiers and marking the noun phrase as definite or indefinite.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] They often agree with the noun in number.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] They do not typically inflect for degree of comparison.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English pronouns conserve many traits of case and gender inflection.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The subjective case corresponds to the Old English nominative case, and the objective case is used in the sense both of the previous accusative case (for a patient, or direct object of a transitive verb), and of the Old English dative case (for a recipient or indirect object of a transitive verb).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The subjective is used when the pronoun is the subject of a finite clause, otherwise the objective is used.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Possessive pronouns exist in dependent and independent forms; the dependent form functions as a determiner specifying a noun (as in *my chair*), while the independent form can stand alone as if it were a noun (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Grammatical person in English no longer distinguishes between formal and informal pronouns of address, with the second person singular familiar pronoun *thou* that previously existed in the language having fallen almost entirely out of use by the 18th century.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Pronouns are used to refer to entities deictically or anaphorically.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] A deictic pronoun points to some person or object by identifying it relative to the speech situation – for example, the pronoun *I* identifies the speaker, and the pronoun *you*, the addressee.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Anaphoric pronouns such as *that* refer back to an entity already mentioned or assumed by the speaker to be known by the audience, for example in the sentence "I already told you that".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The reflexive pronouns are used when the oblique argument is identical to the subject of a phrase (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "he sent it to himself" or "she braced herself for impact").
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Prepositional phrases (PP) are phrases composed of a preposition and one or more nouns, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "with the dog", "for my friend", "to school", "in England".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English prepositions have a wide range of uses – including describing movement, place, and other relations between entities, as well as functions that are syntactic in nature, like introducing complement clauses and oblique arguments of verbs.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrase "I gave it to him", the preposition *to* marks the indirect object of the verb *to give*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Traditionally words were only considered prepositions if they governed the case of the noun they preceded, for example causing the pronouns to use the objective rather than subjective form, "with her", "to me", "for us".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] But some contemporary grammars no longer consider government of case to be the defining feature of the class of prepositions, rather defining prepositions as words that can function as the heads of prepositional phrases.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English verbs are inflected for tense and aspect and marked for agreement with a third person present singular subject.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Only the copula verb *to be* is still inflected for agreement with the plural and first and second person subjects.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs such as *have* and *be* are paired with verbs in the infinitive, past, or progressive forms.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] They form complex tenses, aspects, and moods.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs differ from other verbs in that they can be followed by the negation, and in that they can occur as the first constituent in a question sentence.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The primary forms are a plain present, a third person singular present, and a preterite (past) form.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The secondary forms are a plain form used for the infinitive, a gerund-participle and a past participle.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The verb *to be* – which among other uses in English functions as the primary auxiliary verb indicating the imperfective aspect (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "I *am* going"), as well as the copula – is the only verb to retain some of its original conjugation, and takes different inflectional forms depending on the subject.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The first person present form is *am*, the third person singular form is *is*, and the form *are* is used in the second person singular and all three plurals.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The only verb past participle is *been* and its gerund-participle is *being*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English has two primary tenses, past (preterite) and non-past.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The preterite is inflected by using the preterite form of the verb, which for the regular verbs includes the suffix *-ed*, and for the strong verbs either the suffix *-t* or a change in the stem vowel.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The non-past form is unmarked except in the third person singular, which takes the suffix *-s*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English does not have future verb forms.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The future tense is expressed periphrastically with one of the auxiliary verbs *will* or *shall*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Many varieties also use a near future constructed with the phrasal verb "be going to" (going-to future).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Further aspectual distinctions are shown by auxiliary verbs, primarily *have* and *be*, which show the contrast between a perfect and non-perfect past tense ("I have run" vs.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "I was running"), and compound tenses such as preterite perfect ("I had been running") and present perfect ("I have been running").
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For the expression of mood, English uses a number of modal auxiliaries, such as *can*, *may*, *will*, *shall* and the past tense forms *could*, *might*, *would*, *should*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] There are also subjunctive and imperative moods, both based on the plain form of the verb (i.e. without the third person singular *-s*), for use in subordinate clauses (e.g. subjunctive: "It is important that he run every day"; imperative *Run!*).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] An infinitive form, that uses the plain form of the verb and the preposition *to*, is used for verbal clauses that are syntactically subordinate to a finite verbal clause.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Finite verbal clauses are those that are formed around a verb in the present or preterite form.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In clauses with auxiliary verbs, they are the finite verbs and the main verb is treated as a subordinate clause.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, "he has to go" where only the auxiliary verb *have* is inflected for time and the main verb *to go* is in the infinitive, or in a complement clause such as "I saw him leave", where the main verb is *see*, which is in a preterite form, and *leave* is in the infinitive.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English also makes frequent use of constructions traditionally called phrasal verbs, verb phrases that are made up of a verb root and a preposition or particle that follows the verb.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The phrase then functions as a single predicate.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In terms of intonation the preposition is fused to the verb, but in writing it is written as a separate word.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Examples of phrasal verbs are "to get up", "to ask out", "to get together", and "to put up with".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The phrasal verb frequently has a highly idiomatic meaning that is more specialised and restricted than what can be simply extrapolated from the combination of verb and preposition complement (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] *lay off* meaning *terminate someone's employment*).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Some grammarians do not consider this type of construction to form a syntactic constituent and hence refrain from using the term "phrasal verb".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Instead, they consider the construction simply to be a verb with a prepositional phrase as its syntactic complement, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "he woke up in the morning" and "he ran up in the mountains" are syntactically equivalent.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The function of adverbs is to modify the action or event described by the verb by providing additional information about the manner in which it occurs.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Many English adverbs are derived from adjectives by appending the suffix *-ly*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrase "the woman walked quickly", the adverb *quickly* is derived from the adjective *quick*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Some commonly used adjectives have irregular adverbial forms, such as *good*, which has the adverbial form *well*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Modern English syntax is moderately analytic.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] It has developed features such as modal verbs and word order as resources for conveying meaning.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs mark constructions such as questions, negative polarity, the passive voice and progressive aspect.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English has moved from the Germanic verb-second (V2) word order to being almost exclusively subject–verb–object (SVO).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The combination of SVO order and use of auxiliary verbs often creates clusters of two or more verbs at the centre of the sentence, such as "he had been hoping to try opening it".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In most sentences, English only marks grammatical relations through word order.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The subject constituent precedes the verb and the object constituent follows it.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Indirect objects (IO) of ditransitive verbs can be placed either as the first object in a double object construction (S V IO O), such as "I gave *Jane* the book" or in a prepositional phrase, such as "I gave the book *to Jane*".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English sentences may be composed of one or more clauses, that may in turn be composed of one or more phrases (e.g. noun phrases, verb phrases, prepositional phrases).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] A clause is built around a verb and includes its constituents, such as any noun or prepositional phrases.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Within a sentence, there is always at least one main clause (or matrix clause) whereas other clauses are subordinate to a main clause.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Subordinate clauses may function as arguments of the verb in the main clause.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, in the phrase "I think (that) you are lying", the main clause is headed by the verb *think*, the subject is *I*, but the object of the phrase is the subordinate clause "(that) you are lying".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The subordinating conjunction *that* shows that the clause that follows is a subordinate clause, but it is often omitted.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Relative clauses can be introduced by the pronouns *who*, *whose*, *whom*, and *which* as well as by *that* (which can also be omitted).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In contrast to many other Germanic languages there are no major differences between word order in main and subordinate clauses.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English auxiliary verbs are relied upon for many functions, including the expression of tense, aspect, and mood.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Auxiliary verbs form main clauses, and the main verbs function as heads of a subordinate clause of the auxiliary verb.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, in the sentence "the dog did not find its bone", the clause "find its bone" is the complement of the negated verb *did not*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Subject–auxiliary inversion is used in many constructions, including focus, negation, and interrogative constructions.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Negation is done with the adverb *not*, which precedes the main verb and follows an auxiliary verb.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] A contracted form of not -*n't* can be used as an enclitic attaching to auxiliary verbs and to the copula verb *to be*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Just as with questions, many negative constructions require the negation to occur with *do*-support, thus in Modern English "I don't know him" is the correct answer to the question "Do you know him?", but not *"I know him not", although this construction may be found in older English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Passive constructions also use auxiliary verbs.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] A passive construction rephrases an active construction in such a way that the object of the active phrase becomes the subject of the passive phrase, and the subject of the active phrase is either omitted or demoted to a role as an oblique argument introduced in a prepositional phrase.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] They are formed by using the past participle either with the auxiliary verb *to be* or *to get*, although not all varieties of English allow the use of passives with *get*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, putting the sentence "she sees him" into the passive becomes "he is seen (by her)", or "he gets seen (by her)".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Both yes/no questions and *wh*-questions in English are mostly formed using subject–auxiliary inversion ("Am I going tomorrow?", "Where can we eat?"), which may require *do*-support ("Do you like her?", "Where did he go?").
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In most cases, interrogative words (or wh*-words*) – which include *who*, *what*, *when*, *where*, *why*, and *how* – appear in a fronted position.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, in the question "What did you see?", the word *what* appears as the first constituent despite being the grammatical object of the sentence.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] When the *wh*-word is the subject or forms part of the subject, no inversion occurs (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Prepositional phrases can also be fronted when they are the questions theme (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "To whose house did you go last night?").
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The personal interrogative pronoun *who* is the only interrogative pronoun to still show inflection for case, with the variant *whom* serving as the objective case form, although this form may be going out of use in many contexts.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] While English is a subject-prominent language, at the discourse level it tends to use a topic–comment structure, where the known information (topic) precedes the new information (comment).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Because of the strict SVO syntax, the topic of a sentence generally has to be the grammatical subject of the sentence.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In cases where the topic is not the grammatical subject of the sentence, it is often promoted to subject position through syntactic means.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] One way of doing this is through a passive construction, "the girl was stung by the bee".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Another way is through a cleft sentence where the main clause is demoted to be a complement clause of a copula sentence with a dummy subject such as *it* or *there*, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "it was the girl that the bee stung", "there was a girl who was stung by a bee".
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Dummy subjects are also used in constructions where there is no grammatical subject such as with impersonal verbs (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "it is raining") or in existential clauses ("there are many cars on the street").
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Through the use of these complex sentence constructions with informationally vacuous subjects, English is able to maintain both a topic–comment sentence structure and a SVO syntax.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Focus constructions emphasise a particular piece of new or salient information within a sentence, generally through allocating the main sentence level stress on the focal constituent.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, "the girl was stung by *a bee*" (emphasising it was a bee and not, for example, a wasp that stung her), or "*the girl* was stung by a bee" (contrasting with another possibility, for example that it was the boy).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Topic and focus can also be established through syntactic dislocation, either preposing or postposing the item to be focused on relative to the main clause.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For example, "That girl over there, she was stung by a bee", emphasises the girl by preposition, but a similar effect could be achieved by postposition, "she was stung by a bee, that girl over there", where reference to the girl is established as an afterthought.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Cohesion between sentences is achieved through the use of deictic pronouns as anaphora (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] "that is exactly what I mean" where *that* refers to some fact known to both interlocutors, or *then* used to locate the time of a narrated event relative to the time of a previously narrated event).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Discourse markers such as *oh*, *so*, or *well*, also signal the progression of ideas between sentences and help to create cohesion.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Discourse markers are often the first constituents in sentences.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Discourse markers are also used for stance taking in which speakers position themselves in a specific attitude towards what is being said, for example, "no way is that true!" (the idiomatic marker "no way!" expressing disbelief), or "boy!
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] I'm hungry" (the marker *boy* expressing emphasis).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] While discourse markers are particularly characteristic of informal and spoken registers of English, they are also used in written and formal registers.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The English lexicon consists of around 170,000 words (or 220,000, if counting obsolete words), according to an estimate based on the 1989 edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Over one-half are nouns, one-quarter are adjectives, and one-seventh are verbs.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Another estimate – which includes scientific jargon, prefixed and suffixed words, loanwords of extremely limited use, technical acronyms, etc. – counts around 1 million total English words.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English borrows vocabulary quickly from many languages and other sources.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Early studies of English vocabulary by lexicographers (scholars who study vocabulary and compile dictionaries) were impeded by a lack of comprehensive data on actual vocabulary in use from high-quality linguistic corpora (collections of actual written texts and spoken passages).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Many statements published before the end of the 20th century about the growth of English vocabulary over time, the dates of first use of various words in English, and the sources of English vocabulary will have to be corrected as new computerised analyses of linguistic corpus data become available.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English forms new words from existing words or roots in its vocabulary through a variety of processes.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] One of the most productive processes in English is conversion, using a word with a different grammatical role, for example using a noun as a verb or a verb as a noun.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Another productive word-formation process is nominal compounding, producing compound words such as *babysitter* or *ice cream* or *homesick*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Formation of new words, called neologisms, based on Greek or Latin roots (for example *television* or *optometry*) is a highly productive process in modern European languages like English, so much so that it is often difficult to determine in which language a neologism originated.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] For this reason, American lexicographer Philip Gove attributed many such words to the "international scientific vocabulary" (ISV) when compiling *Webster's Third New International Dictionary* (1961).
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Another active word-formation process in English is that of acronyms, which result from pronouncing abbreviations of longer phrases as single words, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Throughout its history, English has been a particularly frequent borrower of loanwords from other languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] West Germanic words in use since the Anglo-Saxon period still comprise most of the language's core vocabulary, as well as most of its most frequently used words.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Many sentences can be constructed without loanwords, but not without core Anglo-Saxon vocabulary.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English has formal and informal speech registers; informal registers, including child-directed speech, tend to be made up predominantly of Anglo-Saxon vocabulary, while Latinate vocabulary appears more frequently in legal, scientific, and academic writing.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Prolonged and intense contact with French has resulted in English having a very high proportion of Latinate words – with French loanwords borrowed during different stages of the language's history comprising 28 per cent of the English lexicon.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In all periods of its history, English has also borrowed words from Latin directly, representing another 28 per cent of the lexicon.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] In turn, many of these words had originally entered Latin from Greek.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Greek and Latin stems remain highly productive sources for new literary, technical, and scientific vocabulary in English.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Loanwords from Old Norse primarily entered English between the 8th and 11th centuries, during the Norse colonisation of eastern and northern England, and typically displaced an Anglo-Saxon equivalent.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Many represent core vocabulary – including *give*, *get*, *sky*, *skirt*, *egg*, and *cake*.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] English has had a strong influence on the vocabulary of other languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] The influence of English stems from factors such as opinion leaders in other countries knowing the English language, the role of English as a world lingua franca, and the large number of books and films that are translated from English into other languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] This pervasive use of English leads to the conclusion in many places that English is an especially suitable language for expressing new ideas or describing new technologies.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Among the varieties of English, it is especially American English that influences other languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Some languages, such as Chinese, write words borrowed from English mostly as calques, while others, such as Japanese, readily take in English loanwords written in a sound‑indicating script.
[src:bird-s-milk/english-language-p02] Dubbed films and television programmes are a particularly fruitful source of English influence on languages in Europe.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The traditional 32-letter Polish alphabet has nine additions (*ą*, *ć*, *ę*, *ł*, *ń*, *ó*, *ś*, *ź*, *ż*) to the letters of the basic 26-letter Latin alphabet, while removing three (x, q, v).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Those three letters are at times included in an extended 35-letter alphabet.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The traditional set comprises 23 consonants and nine written vowels, including two nasal vowels (*ę*, *ą*) denoted by a reversed diacritic hook called an *ogonek*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish is a synthetic and fusional language which has seven grammatical cases.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] It has fixed penultimate stress and an abundance of palatal consonants.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Contemporary Polish developed in the 1700s as the successor to the medieval Old Polish (10th–16th centuries) and Middle Polish (16th–18th centuries).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Among the major languages, it is most closely related to Slovak and Czech but differs in terms of pronunciation and general grammar.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In addition, Polish was profoundly influenced by Latin and other Romance languages like Italian and French as well as Germanic languages (most notably German), which contributed a large number of loanwords and grammatical structures.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Extensive usage of nonstandard dialects has also shaped the standard language; many colloquialisms and expressions were directly borrowed from German or Yiddish and subsequently adopted into the vernacular of Polish in everyday use.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Historically, Polish was a *lingua franca*, important both diplomatically and academically in Central and part of Eastern Europe.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In addition to being the official language of Poland, Polish is also spoken as a second language in eastern Germany, northern Czech Republic and Slovakia, western parts of Belarus and Ukraine as well as in southeast Lithuania and Latvia.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Because of the emigration from Poland during different time periods, most notably after World War II, millions of Polish speakers can also be found in countries such as Canada, Argentina, Brazil, Israel, Australia, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish began to emerge as a distinct language around the 10th century, the process largely triggered by the establishment and development of the Polish state.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] At the time, it was a collection of dialect groups with some mutual features, but much regional variation was present.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Mieszko I, ruler of the Polans tribe from the Greater Poland region, united a few culturally and linguistically related tribes from the basins of the Vistula and Oder before eventually accepting baptism in 966.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] With the arrival of Western Christianity, Poland also adopted the Latin alphabet, which made it possible to write down Polish, which until then had existed only as a spoken language.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The closest relatives of Polish are the Elbe and Baltic Sea Lechitic dialects (Polabian and Pomeranian varieties).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] All of them, except Kashubian, are extinct.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The precursor to modern Polish is the Old Polish language.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Ultimately, Polish descends from the unattested Proto-Slavic language.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The book is exhibited in the Archdiocesal Museum in Wrocław, and as of 2015 has been added to UNESCO's "Memory of the World" list.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The medieval recorder of this phrase, the Cistercian monk Peter of the Henryków monastery, noted that "Hoc est in polonico" ("This is in Polish").
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The earliest treatise on Polish orthography was written by Jakub Parkosz around 1470.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The first printed book in Polish appeared in either 1508 or 1513, while the oldest Polish newspaper was established in 1661.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Starting in the 1520s, large numbers of books in the Polish language were published, contributing to increased homogeneity of grammar and orthography.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The writing system achieved its overall form in the 16th century, which is also regarded as the "Golden Age of Polish literature".
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The orthography was modified in the 19th century and in 1936.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The history of Polish as a language of state governance begins in the 16th century in the Kingdom of Poland.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Over the later centuries, Polish served as the official language in the Grand Duchy of Lithuania, Congress Poland, the Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria, and as the administrative language in the Russian Empire's Western Krai.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The growth of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth's influence gave Polish the status of *lingua franca* in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The process of standardization began in the 14th century and solidified in the 16th century during the Middle Polish era.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Standard Polish was based on various dialectal features, with the Greater Poland dialect group serving as the base.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] After World War II, Standard Polish became the most widely spoken variant of Polish across the country, and most dialects stopped being the form of Polish spoken in villages.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Poland is one of the most linguistically homogeneous European countries; nearly 97% of Poland's citizens declare Polish as their first language.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Elsewhere, Poles constitute large minorities in areas which were once administered or occupied by Poland, notably in neighboring Lithuania, Belarus, and Ukraine.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish is the most widely used minority language in Lithuania's Vilnius County, by 26% of the population, according to the 2001 census results, as Vilnius was part of Poland from 1922 until 1939.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish is found elsewhere in southeastern Lithuania.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In Ukraine, it is most common in the western parts of Lviv and Volyn Oblasts, while in West Belarus it is used by the significant Polish minority, especially in the Brest and Grodno regions and in areas along the Lithuanian border.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] There are significant numbers of Polish speakers among Polish emigrants and their descendants in many other countries.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In the United States, Polish Americans number more than 11 million but most of them cannot speak Polish fluently.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] According to the 2000 United States census, 667,414 Americans of age five years and over reported Polish as the language spoken at home, which is about 1.4% of people who speak languages other than English, 0.25% of the US population, and 6% of the Polish-American population.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The largest concentrations of Polish speakers reported in the census (over 50%) were found in three states: Illinois (185,749), New York (111,740), and New Jersey (74,663).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Enough people in these areas speak Polish that PNC Financial Services (which has a large number of branches in all of these areas) offers services available in Polish at all of their cash machines in addition to English and Spanish.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] According to the 2011 census there are now over 500,000 people in England and Wales who consider Polish to be their "main" language.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In Canada, there is a significant Polish Canadian population: There are 242,885 speakers of Polish according to the 2006 census; in particular, there are concentrations of Polish speakers in Toronto (91,810 speakers) and Montreal.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The geographical distribution of the Polish language was greatly affected by the territorial changes of Poland immediately after World War II and Polish population transfers (1944–46).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Poles settled in the "Recovered Territories" in the west and north, which had previously been mostly German-speaking.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Some Poles remained in the previously Polish-ruled territories in the east that were annexed by the USSR, resulting in the present-day Polish-speaking communities in Lithuania, Belarus, and Ukraine, although many Poles were expelled from those areas to areas within Poland's new borders.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] To the east of Poland, the most significant Polish minority lives in a long strip along either side of the Lithuania-Belarus border.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Meanwhile, the flight and expulsion of Germans (1944–50), as well as the expulsion of Ukrainians and Operation Vistula, the 1947 migration of Ukrainian minorities in the Recovered Territories in the west of the country, contributed to the country's linguistic homogeneity.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] ), that became part of Poland after World War II.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Geographical distribution of the Polish language (green) and other Central and Eastern European languages and dialects.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish is not a majority language of any nation outside of Poland, though areas that speak and are majority Polish are present in some neighboring countries.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The inhabitants of different regions of Poland still speak Polish somewhat differently, although the differences between modern-day vernacular varieties and standard Polish (*język ogólnopolski*) appear relatively slight.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Most of the middle aged and young speak vernaculars close to standard Polish, while the traditional dialects are preserved among older people in rural areas.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] First-language speakers of Polish have no trouble understanding each other, and non-native speakers may have difficulty recognizing the regional and social differences.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The modern standard dialect, often termed as "correct Polish", is spoken or at least understood throughout the entire country.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Silesian and Kashubian, spoken in Upper Silesia and Pomerania respectively, are thought of as either Polish dialects or distinct languages, depending on the criteria used.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] However, it was described by some linguists as lacking most of the linguistic and social determinants of language-hood.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Many linguistic sources categorize Silesian as a regional language separate from Polish, while some consider Silesian to be a dialect of Polish.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Many Silesians consider themselves a separate ethnicity and have been advocating for the recognition of Silesian as a regional language in Poland.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The law recognizing it as such was passed by the Sejm and Senate in April 2024, but was vetoed by President Andrzej Duda in late May 2024.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] According to the last official census in Poland in 2011, over half a million people declared Silesian as their native language.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Tomasz Kamusella, Agnieszka Pianka, Alfred F.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Majewicz, Tomasz Wicherkiewicz) assume that extralinguistic criteria decide whether a lect is an independent language or a dialect: speakers of the speech variety or/and political decisions, and this is dynamic (i.e. it changes over time).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Also, research organizations such as SIL International and resources for the academic field of linguistics such as *Ethnologue*, Linguist List and others, for example the Ministry of Administration and Digitization recognized the Silesian language.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In July 2007, the Silesian language was recognized by ISO, and was attributed an ISO code of szl.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Poznański dialect, spoken in Poznań and to some extent in the whole region of the former Prussian Partition (excluding Upper Silesia), with noticeable German influences.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In the northern and western (formerly German) regions where Poles from the territories annexed by the Soviet Union resettled after World War II, the older generation speaks a dialect of Polish characteristic of the Kresy that includes a longer pronunciation of vowels.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Some city dwellers, especially the less affluent population, had their own distinctive dialects – for example, the Warsaw dialect, still spoken by some of the population of Praga on the eastern bank of the Vistula.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] However, these city dialects are now mostly extinct due to assimilation with standard Polish.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Many Poles living in emigrant communities (for example, in the United States), whose families left Poland just after World War II, retain a number of minor features of Polish vocabulary as spoken in the first half of the 20th century that now sound archaic to contemporary visitors from Poland.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish linguistics has been characterized by a strong strive towards promoting prescriptive ideas of language intervention and usage uniformity, along with normatively oriented notions of language "correctness" (unusual by Western standards).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish has six oral vowels (seven oral vowels in written form), which are all monophthongs, and two nasal vowels.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The oral vowels are /i/ (spelled *i*), /ɨ/ (spelled *y* and also transcribed as /ɘ/ or /ɪ/), /ɛ/ (spelled *e*), /a/ (spelled *a*), /ɔ/ (spelled *o*) and /u/ (spelled *u* and *ó* as separate letters).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The nasal vowels are /ɛw̃/ (spelled *ę*) and /ɔw̃/ (spelled *ą*).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Unlike Czech or Slovak, Polish does not retain phonemic vowel length — the letter *ó*, which formerly represented lengthened /ɔː/ in older forms of the language, is now vestigial and instead corresponds to /u/.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Polish consonant system shows more complexity: its characteristic features include the series of affricate and palatal consonants that resulted from four Proto-Slavic palatalizations and two further palatalizations that took place in Polish.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Neutralization occurs between voiced–voiceless consonant pairs in certain environments, at the end of words (where devoicing occurs) and in certain consonant clusters (where assimilation occurs).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] For details, see *Voicing and devoicing* in the article on Polish phonology.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Most Polish words are paroxytones (that is, the stress falls on the second-to-last syllable of a polysyllabic word), although there are exceptions.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish permits complex consonant clusters, which historically often arose from the disappearance of yers.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish can have word-initial and word-medial clusters of up to four consonants, whereas word-final clusters can have up to five consonants.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Examples of such clusters can be found in words such as *bezwzględny*ⓘ [bɛzˈvzɡlɛndnɨ] ('absolute' or 'heartless', 'ruthless'), *źdźbło*ⓘ [ˈʑd͡ʑbwɔ] ('blade of grass'), *wstrząs*ⓘ [ˈfstʂɔw̃s] ('shock'), and *krnąbrność* [ˈkrnɔmbrnɔɕt͡ɕ] ('disobedience').
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] A popular Polish tongue-twister (from a verse by Jan Brzechwa) is *W Szczebrzeszynie chrząszcz brzmi w trzcinie*ⓘ [fʂt͡ʂɛbʐɛˈʂɨɲɛ ˈxʂɔw̃ʂt͡ʂ ˈbʐmi fˈtʂt͡ɕiɲɛ] ('In Szczebrzeszyn a beetle buzzes in the reed').
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Unlike languages such as Czech, Polish does not have syllabic consonants – the nucleus of a syllable is always a vowel.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The consonant /j/ is restricted to positions adjacent to a vowel.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The predominant stress pattern in Polish is penultimate stress – in a word of more than one syllable, the next-to-last syllable is stressed.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Alternating preceding syllables carry secondary stress, e.g. in a four-syllable word, where the primary stress is on the third syllable, there will be secondary stress on the first.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Each vowel represents one syllable, although the letter *i* normally does not represent a vowel when it precedes another vowel (it represents /j/, palatalization of the preceding consonant, or both depending on analysis).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Also the letters *u* and *i* sometimes represent only semivowels when they follow another vowel, as in *autor* /ˈawtɔr/ ('author'), mostly in loanwords (so not in native *nauka* /naˈu.ka/ 'science, the act of learning', for example, nor in nativized *Mateusz* /maˈte.uʂ/ 'Matthew').
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Some loanwords, particularly from the classical languages, have the stress on the antepenultimate (third-from-last) syllable.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] For example, *fizyka* (/ˈfizɨka/) ('physics') is stressed on the first syllable.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] This may lead to a rare phenomenon of minimal pairs differing only in stress placement, for example *muzyka* /ˈmuzɨka/ 'music' vs.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] *muzyka* /muˈzɨka/ – genitive singular of *muzyk* 'musician'.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] When additional syllables are added to such words through inflection or suffixation, the stress normally becomes regular.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] For example, *uniwersytet* (/uɲiˈvɛrsɨtɛt/, 'university') has irregular stress on the third (or antepenultimate) syllable, but the genitive *uniwersytetu* (/uɲivɛrsɨˈtɛtu/) and derived adjective *uniwersytecki* (/uɲivɛrsɨˈtɛt͡skʲi/) have regular stress on the penultimate syllables.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Loanwords generally become nativized to have penultimate stress.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In psycholinguistic experiments, speakers of Polish have been demonstrated to be sensitive to the distinction between regular penultimate and exceptional antepenultimate stress.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Another class of exceptions is verbs with the conditional endings *-by, -bym, -byśmy*, etc.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] These endings are not counted in determining the position of the stress; for example, ***zro**biłbym* ('I would do') is stressed on the first syllable, and *zro**bi**libyśmy* ('we would do') on the second.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Reanalysis of the endings as inflections when attached to verbs causes the different colloquial stress patterns.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] These stress patterns are considered part of a "usable" norm of standard Polish - in contrast to the "model" ("high") norm.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Some common word combinations are stressed as if they were a single word.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] This applies in particular to many combinations of preposition plus a personal pronoun, such as ***do** niej* ('to her'), ***na** nas* ('on us'), *prze**ze** mnie* ('because of me'), all stressed on the bolded syllable.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Polish alphabet derives from the Latin script but includes certain additional letters formed using diacritics.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Polish alphabet was one of three major forms of Latin-based orthography developed for Western and some South Slavic languages, the others being Czech orthography and Croatian orthography, the last of these being a 19th-century invention trying to make a compromise between the first two.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Kashubian uses a Polish-based system, Slovak uses a Czech-based system, and Slovene follows the Croatian one; the Sorbian languages blend the Polish and the Czech ones.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Historically, Poland's once diverse and multi-ethnic population utilized many forms of scripture to write Polish.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] For instance, Lipka Tatars and Muslims inhabiting the eastern parts of the former Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth wrote Polish in the Arabic alphabet.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Cyrillic script is used to a certain extent today by Polish speakers in Western Belarus, especially for religious texts.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The diacritics used in the Polish alphabet are the *kreska* (graphically similar to the acute accent) over the letters *ć, ń, ó, ś, ź* and through the letter in *ł*; the *kropka* (superior dot) over the letter *ż*, and the *ogonek* ("little tail") under the letters *ą, ę*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The letters *q, v, x* are used only in foreign words and names.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish orthography is largely phonemic—there is a consistent correspondence between letters (or digraphs and trigraphs) and phonemes (for exceptions see below).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The letters of the alphabet and their normal phonemic values are listed in the following table.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Voiced consonant letters frequently come to represent voiceless sounds (as shown in the tables); this occurs at the end of words and in certain clusters, due to the neutralization mentioned in the *Phonology* section above.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Occasionally also voiceless consonant letters can represent voiced sounds in clusters.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The spelling rule for the palatal sounds /ɕ/, /ʑ/, /tɕ/, /dʑ/ and /ɲ/ is as follows: before the vowel *i* the plain letters *s, z, c, dz, n* are used; before other vowels the combinations *si, zi, ci, dzi, ni* are used; when not followed by a vowel the diacritic forms *ś, ź, ć, dź, ń* are used.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] For example, the *s* in *siwy* ("grey-haired"), the *si* in *siarka* ("sulfur") and the *ś* in *święty* ("holy") all represent the sound /ɕ/.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The exceptions to the above rule are certain loanwords from Latin, Italian, French, Russian or English—where *s* before *i* is pronounced as *s*, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] *sinus*, *sinologia*, *do re mi fa sol la si do*, *Saint-Simon i saint-simoniści*, *Sierioża*, *Siergiej*, *Singapur*, *singiel*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In other loanwords the vowel *i* is changed to *y*, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Similar principles apply to /kʲ/, /ɡʲ/, /xʲ/ and /lʲ/, except that these can only occur before vowels, so the spellings are *k, g, (c)h, l* before *i*, and *ki, gi, (c)hi, li* otherwise.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Most Polish speakers, however, do not consider palatalization of *k, g, (c)h* or *l* as creating new sounds.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Except in the cases mentioned above, the letter *i* if followed by another vowel in the same word usually represents /j/, yet a palatalization of the previous consonant is always assumed.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The reverse case, where the consonant remains unpalatalized but is followed by a palatalized consonant, is written by using *j* instead of *i*: for example, *zjeść*, "to eat up".
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The letters *ą* and *ę*, when followed by plosives and affricates, represent an oral vowel followed by a nasal consonant, rather than a nasal vowel.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] For example, *ą* in *dąb* ("oak") is pronounced [ɔm], and *ę* in *tęcza* ("rainbow") is pronounced [ɛn] (the nasal assimilates to the following consonant).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] When followed by *l* or *ł* (for example *przyjęli*, *przyjęły*), *ę* is pronounced as just *e*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] When *ę* is at the end of the word it is often pronounced as just [ɛ].
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Depending on the word, the phoneme /x/ can be spelt *h* or *ch*, the phoneme /ʐ/ can be spelt *ż* or *rz*, and /u/ can be spelt *u* or *ó*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In several cases it determines the meaning, for example: *może* ("maybe") and *morze* ("sea").
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In occasional words, letters that normally form a digraph are pronounced separately.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] For example, *rz* represents /rz/, not /ʐ/, in words like *zamarzać* ("freeze") and in the name **Tarzan**.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Doubled letters are usually pronounced as a single, lengthened consonant, however, some speakers might pronounce the combination as two separate sounds.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] There are certain clusters where a written consonant would not be pronounced.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] For example, the *ł* in the word *jabłko* ("apple") might be omitted in ordinary speech, leading to the pronunciation *japko*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish is a highly fusional language with relatively free word order, although the dominant arrangement is subject–verb–object (SVO).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] There are no articles, and subject pronouns are often dropped.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Nouns belong to one of three genders: masculine, feminine and neuter.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The masculine gender is also divided into subgenders: animate vs inanimate in the singular, human vs nonhuman in the plural.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] There are seven cases: nominative, genitive, dative, accusative, instrumental, locative and vocative.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Adjectives agree with nouns in terms of gender, case, and number.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Attributive adjectives most commonly precede the noun, although in certain cases, especially in fixed phrases (like *język polski*, "Polish (language)"), the noun may come first; the rule of thumb is that generic descriptive adjectives normally precede (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] *piękny kwiat*, "beautiful flower") while categorizing adjectives often follow the noun (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Most short adjectives and their derived adverbs form comparatives and superlatives by inflection (the superlative is formed by prefixing *naj-* to the comparative).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Verbs are of imperfective or perfective aspect, often occurring in pairs.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Perfective verbs have a simple future tense (formed like the present tense of imperfective verbs), past tense, subjunctive/conditional, imperatives, infinitive, present gerund and past participle.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Conjugated verb forms agree with their subject in terms of person, number, and (in the case of past tense and subjunctive/conditional forms) gender.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Passive-type constructions can be made using the auxiliary *być* or *zostać* ("become") with the passive participle.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] There is also an impersonal construction where the active verb is used (in third person singular) with no subject, but with the reflexive pronoun *się* present to indicate a general, unspecified subject (as in *pije się wódkę* "vodka is being drunk"—note that *wódka* appears in the accusative).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] A similar sentence type in the past tense uses the passive participle with the ending *-o*, as in *widziano ludzi* ("people were seen").
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] As in other Slavic languages, there are also subjectless sentences formed using such words as *można* ("it is possible") together with an infinitive.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Yes–no questions (both direct and indirect) are formed by placing the word *czy* ("whether") at the start, although it's often omitted in casual speech.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Negation uses the word *nie*, before the verb or other item being negated; *nie* is still added before the verb even if the sentence also contains other negatives such as *nigdy* ("never") or *nic* ("nothing"), effectively creating a double negative.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Cardinal numbers have a complex system of inflection and agreement.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Zero and cardinal numbers higher than five (except for those ending with the digit 2, 3 or 4 but not ending with 12, 13 or 14) govern the genitive case rather than the nominative or accusative.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Special forms of numbers (collective numerals) are used with certain classes of noun, which include *dziecko* ("child") and exclusively plural nouns such as *drzwi* ("door").
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Poland was once a multi-ethnic nation with many minorities that contributed to the Polish language.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Top right: rope (*sznur* from German *Schnur*).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Bottom left: shark (*rekin* from French *requin*).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish has, over the centuries, borrowed a number of words from other languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] When borrowing, pronunciation was adapted to Polish phonemes and spelling was altered to match Polish orthography.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In addition, word endings are liberally applied to almost any word to produce verbs, nouns, adjectives, as well as adding the appropriate endings for cases of nouns, adjectives, diminutives, double-diminutives, augmentatives, etc.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Depending on the historical period, borrowing has proceeded from various languages.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Notable influences have been Latin (10th–18th centuries), Czech (10th and 14th–15th centuries), Italian (16th–17th centuries), French (17th–19th centuries), German (13–15th and 18th–20th centuries), Hungarian (15th–16th centuries) and Turkish (17th century).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Currently, English words are the most common imports to Polish.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Latin language, for a very long time the only official language of the Polish state, has had a great influence on Polish.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Many Polish words were direct borrowings or calques (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] *rzeczpospolita* from *res publica*) from Latin.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Latin was known to a larger or smaller degree by most of the numerous szlachta in the 16th to 18th centuries (and it continued to be extensively taught at secondary schools until World War II).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Apart from dozens of loanwords, its influence can also be seen in a number of verbatim Latin phrases in Polish literature (especially from the 19th century and earlier).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] During the 12th and 13th centuries, Mongolian words were brought to the Polish language during wars with the armies of Genghis Khan and his descendants, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] *dzida* (spear) and *szereg* (a line or row).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Words from Czech, an important influence during the 10th and 14th–15th centuries include *sejm*, *hańba* and *brama*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In 1518, the Polish king Sigismund I the Old married Bona Sforza, the niece of the Holy Roman emperor Maximilian, who introduced Italian cuisine to Poland, especially vegetables.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Hence, words from Italian include *pomidor* from "pomodoro" (tomato), *kalafior* from "cavolfiore" (cauliflower), and *pomarańcza*, a portmanteau from Italian "pomo" (pome) plus "arancio" (orange).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] A later word of Italian origin is *autostrada* (from Italian "autostrada", highway).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In the 18th century, with the rising prominence of France in Europe, French supplanted Latin as an important source of words.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Some French borrowings also date from the Napoleonic era, when the Poles were enthusiastic supporters of Napoleon.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Some place names have also been adapted from French, such as the Warsaw boroughs of Żoliborz ("joli bord" = beautiful riverside), Marymont ("Marie mont" = Mary's hill) as well as the town of Żyrardów (from the name Girard, with the Polish suffix -ów attached to refer to the founder of the town).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Many words were borrowed from the German language from the sizable German population in Polish cities during medieval times.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] German words found in the Polish language are often connected with trade, the building industry, civic rights and city life.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Some words were assimilated verbatim, for example *handel* (trade) and *dach* (roof); others are pronounced similarly, but differ in writing *Schnur*—*sznur* (cord).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] As a result of being neighbors with Germany, Polish has many German expressions which have become literally translated (calques).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The regional dialects of Upper Silesia and Masuria (Modern Polish East Prussia) have noticeably more German loanwords than other varieties.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The contacts with Ottoman Turkey in the 17th century brought many new words, some of them still in use, such as: *jar* ("yar" deep valley), *szaszłyk* ("şişlik" shish kebab), *filiżanka* ("fincan" cup), *arbuz* ("karpuz" watermelon), *dywan* ("divan" carpet), etc.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] From the founding of the Kingdom of Poland in 1025 through the early years of the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth created in 1569, Poland was the most tolerant country of Jews in Europe.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Known as the "paradise for the Jews", it became a shelter for persecuted and expelled European Jewish communities and the home to the world's largest Jewish community of the time.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] As a result, many Polish words come from Yiddish, spoken by the large Polish Jewish population that existed until the Holocaust.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The mountain dialects of the Górale in southern Poland, have quite a number of words borrowed from Hungarian (e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] *baca*, *gazda*, *juhas*, *hejnał*) and Romanian as a result of historical contacts with Hungarian-dominated Slovakia and Wallachian herders who travelled north along the Carpathians.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Thieves' slang includes such words as *kimać* (to sleep) or *majcher* (knife) of Greek origin, considered then unknown to the outside world.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In addition, Turkish and Tatar have exerted influence upon the vocabulary of war, names of oriental costumes etc.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Russian borrowings began to make their way into Polish from the second half of the 19th century on.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Polish has also received an intensive number of English loanwords, particularly after World War II.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Recent loanwords come primarily from the English language, mainly those that have Latin or Greek roots, for example *komputer* (computer), *korupcja* (from 'corruption', but sense restricted to 'bribery') etc.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] *auto-moto*), which is not native to Polish but common in English, for example, is also sometimes used.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] When borrowing English words, Polish often changes their spelling.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] For example, Latin suffix '-tio' corresponds to *-cja*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] To make the word plural, *-cja* becomes *-cje*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Examples of this include *inauguracja* (inauguration), *dewastacja* (devastation), *recepcja* (reception), *konurbacja* (conurbation) and *konotacje* (connotations).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Also, the digraph *qu* becomes *kw* (*kwadrant* = quadrant; *kworum* = quorum).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Polish language has influenced others.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Particular influences appear in other Slavic languages and in German — due to their proximity and shared borders.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The common Germanic word *quartz* comes from the dialectical Old Polish *kwardy*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] "Szmata," a Polish, Slovak and Ruthenian word for "mop" or "rag", became part of Yiddish.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Polish language exerted significant lexical influence upon Ukrainian, particularly in the fields of abstract and technical terminology; for example, the Ukrainian word панство *panstvo* (country) is derived from Polish *państwo*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Polish influence on Ukrainian is particularly marked on western Ukrainian dialects in western Ukraine, which for centuries was under Polish cultural domination.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] There are a substantial number of Polish words which officially became part of Yiddish, once the main language of European Jews.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] These include basic items, objects or terms such as a bread bun (Polish *bułka*, Yiddish בולקע *bulke*), a fishing rod (*wędka*, ווענטקע *ventke*), an oak (*dąb*, דעמב *demb*), a meadow (*łąka*, לאָנקע *lonke*), a moustache (*wąsy*, וואָנצעס *vontses*) and a bladder (*pęcherz*, פּענכער *penkher*).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Quite a few culinary loanwords exist in German and in other languages, some of which describe distinctive features of Polish cuisine.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] These include German and English *Quark* from *twaróg* (a kind of fresh cheese) and German *Gurke*, English *gherkin* from *ogórek* (cucumber).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The word *pierogi* (Polish dumplings) has spread internationally, as well as *pączki* (Polish donuts) and kiełbasa (sausage, e.g.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] As far as *pierogi* concerned, the original Polish word is already in plural (sing.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] *pieróg*, plural *pierogi*; stem *pierog-*, plural ending *-i*; NB.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] *o* becomes *ó* in a closed syllable, like here in singular), yet it is commonly used with the English plural ending *-s* in Canada and United States of America, *pierogis*, thus making it a "double plural".
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] A similar situation happened with the Polish loanword from English *czipsy* ("potato chips")—from English *chips* being already plural in the original (*chip* + *-s*), yet it has obtained the Polish plural ending *-y*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] It is believed that the English word *spruce* was derived from *Prusy*, the Polish name for the region of Prussia.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] It became *spruce* because in Polish, *z Prus*, sounded like "spruce" in English (transl.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] "from Prussia") and was a generic term for commodities brought to England by Hanseatic merchants and because the tree was believed to have come from Polish Ducal Prussia.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] However, it can be argued that the word is actually derived from the Old French term *Pruce*, meaning literally Prussia.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The Polish language started to be used in literature in the Late Middle Ages.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Notable works include the *Holy Cross Sermons* (13th/14th century), *Bogurodzica* (15th century) and *Master Polikarp's Dialog with Death* (15th century).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] During the Age of Enlightenment in Poland, Ignacy Krasicki, known as "the Prince of Poets", wrote the first Polish novel called *The Adventures of Mr.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Nicholas Wisdom* as well as *Fables and Parables*.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Another significant work form this period is *The Manuscript Found in Saragossa* by Jan Potocki.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] In the Romantic Era, the most celebrated national poets, referred to as the Three Bards, were Adam Mickiewicz (*Pan Tadeusz* and *Dziady*), Juliusz Słowacki (*Balladyna*) and Zygmunt Krasiński (*The Undivine Comedy*).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Poet and dramatist Cyprian Norwid is regarded by some scholars as the "Fourth Bard".
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The period known as Young Poland produced such renowned literary figures as Stanisław Wyspiański (*The Wedding*), Stefan Żeromski (*Homeless People*, *The Spring to Come*), Władysław Reymont (*The Peasants*) and Leopold Staff.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] The prominent interbellum period authors include Maria Dąbrowska (*Nights and Days*), Stanisław Ignacy Witkiewicz (*Insatiability*), Julian Tuwim, Bruno Schulz, Bolesław Leśmian, Witold Gombrowicz and Zuzanna Ginczanka.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Five people writing in the Polish language have been awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature: Henryk Sienkiewicz (1905), Władysław Reymont (1924), Czesław Miłosz (1980), Wisława Szymborska (1996) and Olga Tokarczuk (2018).
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Wszyscy ludzie rodzą się wolni i równi pod względem swej godności i swych praw.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] Są oni obdarzeni rozumem i sumieniem i powinni postępować wobec innych w duchu braterstwa.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.
[src:bird-s-milk/polish-language] They are endowed with reason and conscience and should act towards one another in a spirit of brotherhood.
